MLPs are a class of feed-forward deep neural network that consist of multiple, fully-connected (i.e., dense) hidden layers. In MLPs, the mapping f between the pre- and post-impact parameters is defined by a composition of functions g1,g2,…,gn\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$g_{1}, g_{2}, \ldots, g_{n}$\end{document} (n being the number of layers in the network), yielding, 5f(x→)=gn(⋯g2(g1(x→))),\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ f(\vec{x}) = g_{n} \bigl( \cdots g_{2} \bigl( g_{1} (\vec{x} ) \bigr) \bigr) , $$\end{document} where each function gi(wi,bi,hi(⋅))\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$g_{i}(w_{i},b_{i},h_{i}(\cdot ))$\end{document} is parameterized by a weights matrix (wi\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$w_{i}$\end{document}), a bias vector (bi\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$b_{i}$\end{document}), and an activation function (hi(⋅)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$h_{i}(\cdot )$\end{document}). The weights matrix and bias vector are the parameters of the network that are tuned by minimizing a loss function which measures how well the mapping f performs on a given dataset. In this work, the MLPs are implemented with Python’s Keras library and models consist of an input layer with 12 nodes, one to three hidden layers with up to 24 nodes each, and an output layer with a single node (i.e., a scalar output). All activation functions in the resulting network are the Rectified Linear Unit (ReLU). A detailed overview of the MLPs used in this work is provided in Appendix G.

The procedure for standardizing the input data differs between PCE and the other data-driven methods. In the case of PCE, the input parameters are linearly mapped into a hypercube [−1,1]12\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$[-1,1]^{12}$\end{document}, within which the distribution of the transformed features is still uniform.

For the other methods, the pre- and post-impact parameters are scaled using the standard scaling method. The result of standardization (a.k.a. Z-score normalization) is that the features will be rescaled such that they evince the properties of a standard normal distribution, μ=0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\mu = 0$\end{document} and σ=1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\sigma = 1$\end{document}, where μ and σ are the mean and standard deviation of the distribution, respectively. The z-values are then calculated as, 6z=x−μσ.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ z = \frac{x - \mu }{\sigma } . $$\end{document}

